GLHF!

I have, for a time, been using <a title="CloudFlare Website" href="http://www.cloudflare.com" target="_blank">CloudFlare </a>for CDN, Optimizations and DNS Management for this and a few other domains. At the same time, I've been using <a title="Dyn DNS" href="http://www.dyn.com" target="_blank">DynDNS </a>to provide name resolution to my home network/lab. Browsing around the <a title="CloudFlare Client Api" href="https://www.cloudflare.com/docs/client-api.html" target="_blank">CloudFlare JSONAPI</a> I noticed that I can update DNS records throughsome fairly simple HTTP GET requests, and since the RouterOS (the operating system used by <a title="Mikrotik Website" href="http://www.mikrotik.com/" target="_blank">Mikrotiks </a>routerboards) has support for some pretty decent scripting I decided to let my router update CloudFlare for some custom and free dynamic DNS resolution.
